<http://purl.unep.org/sdg/SDGIO_00000020> a owl:Class;
  rdfs:subClassOf <http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/BFO_0000016>;
  <http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000114> <http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000125>;
  <http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000115> "A disposition of a bearer to realise one or more of its vulnerabilities when participating in a process which exposes the bearer to a hazard or combination of hazards.";
  <http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000116> "https://github.com/SDG-InterfaceOntology/sdgio/issues/22";
  <http://purl.unep.org/sdg/SDGIO_00000064> "https://uneplive.unep.org/community/discussion/view/23229/risk";
  <http://purl.unep.org/sdg/SDGIO_00010058> "The possibility that an entity's vulnerabilities will be realised when exposed to a hazard.";
  rdfs:comment "Risk is increased when harm or damage is realised and when an entity is likely to encounter a hazard in some process.  The probability of this disposition being realised can be assigned on the information or data level.";
  rdfs:label "risk"@en .

<http://purl.unep.org/sdg/SDGIO_00010017> a owl:Class;
  rdfs:subClassOf <http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/BFO_0000023>;
  <http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000115> "A role which is realised by an entity when it confers some benefit to its consumer."@en;
  rdfs:comment "Dependent continuants (eg- information) and processes (eg- essential services) are also considered resources. As such these \"abstract\" resources cannot bear roles. Plausibly it is the independent continuants that participate in such processes (the computer that allows access to the information), or are the bearers of information (the computer's memory disk), which are rightfully considered the resource."@en;
  rdfs:label "resource role"@en .

_:genid21 a owl:Axiom;
  owl:annotatedSource <http://purl.unep.org/sdg/SDGIO_00010017>;
  owl:annotatedProperty rdfs:comment;
  owl:annotatedTarget "Dependent continuants (eg- information) and processes (eg- essential services) are also considered resources. As such these \"abstract\" resources cannot bear roles. Plausibly it is the independent continuants that participate in such processes (the computer that allows access to the information), or are the bearers of information (the computer's memory disk), which are rightfully considered the resource."@en;
  rdfs:comment """ClimOO developer comment:
Revisions are required to deal with such shortcomings."""@en .
